Buchanan, XIII. 22, says James had so drained his coflers by building palaces, ships, etc„ that, on the advice of Elphinstone, he revived a law which had been allowed to lapse, that the king or any other lord on whom the wardship of an heir devolved, was authorised to take all the rents and proiits of the estate until the heir came of age. If the proprietor sold above half of his estate without the consent of the superior, the whole fell into the hands of the latter. Buchanan is the only writer who has tried to bring discredit on Elphinstone. Even he is forced to admit that the reverence felt for the lting made his subjecta submit to this law.
